  "slug": "game-pie",
  "title": "Game Pie",
  "subtitle": "Mixed game braised in red wine and juniper, in a shortcrust pastry case",
  "excerpt": "A game pie uses whatever is in season or available: typically venison, pheasant breast, and rabbit, braised low and slow in red wine before being enclosed in a shortcrust pastry case and baked. It is served hot in winter and cold in summer.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Traditional British raised pie tradition. Jane Grigson, English Food (1974): game pie with mixed game. Hugh Fearnley-Whittingstall, The River Cottage Meat Book (2004): game pie with red wine and juniper. Cross-referenced across multiple sources.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A game pie is flexible by nature: use what is available. Venison dice, pheasant breast, and rabbit legs are a classic combination, but the method works with any game. The filling is ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "braised",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr442g0000a8v4vc0j2z2g"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " the day before, cooled completely, and then enclosed in pastry. A warm filling will make the pastry greasy and prevent a clean cut.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Game pie tastes best between October and February, when pheasant and venison come into season. Outside that window, farmed venison and frozen game work well too."
          }
        ]
      },
