      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Braise the game",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 160°C (140°C fan). Fry the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{lardons}} of lardons",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " in a casserole until crisp. Remove and set aside. In the same fat, brown the venison and rabbit pieces in batches, then remove. Soften the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{onion}} onions",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and carrots in the casserole for 5 minutes. Add the garlic, ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{juniper-berries}} juniper berries",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ", thyme, and bay leaves. Return the meat and lardons. Pour over the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{red-wine}} of red wine",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{stock-beef}} of beef stock",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Season with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sea-salt-flakes}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{black-pepper}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Cover and braise for 2 hours. Cool completely; refrigerate overnight.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Assemble and bake",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 200°C (180°C fan). Pick out the bones from the rabbit pieces and discard. Roll two thirds of the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{shortcrust-pastry}} of shortcrust pastry",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and use it to line a deep 25 cm pie dish. Spoon in the cold filling, leaving 1 cm of headspace. Moisten the pastry rim with water, then lay the remaining pastry as a lid and seal. Trim and crimp the edges. Make a steam vent in the centre. Brush with beaten egg and bake for 20 minutes. Reduce to 180°C and bake for a further 25-30 minutes until deeply golden. Rest for 15 minutes before slicing.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "Reduce the braising liquid by a third before cooling if it seems very thin. Leave 1 cm of headroom in the dish.",
              "cause": "Filling was too liquid, or too much was used",
              "symptom": "Filling spills over the pastry rim during baking"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Run fingers through the braised rabbit meat carefully before filling the pie. Rabbit leg bones are obvious; the risk is small rib bones.",
              "cause": "Small bones are hard to find in the braised meat",
              "symptom": "Rabbit bones in the sliced pie"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use a pie tin rather than a ceramic dish for better base heat conduction. The filling must be cold.",
              "cause": "Filling was too wet or the dish too deep",
              "symptom": "Pastry base is under-baked"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Soaking diced game in cold water for 1 hour before browning draws out some blood and reduces strong flavour.",
              "cause": "Later-season birds, or venison from a wild animal rather than farmed",
              "symptom": "Game flavour is very strong"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Game pie has appeared on the British table in winter since at least the Tudor period, made from whatever was shot on the estate. The modern version draws on the French and British traditions equally: a braised filling with wine and herbs, a shortcrust pastry case, and the pleasure of a slice that holds its shape. It is a cold-weather centrepiece.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
